{{Distinguish | Contrafactum}} {{for|borrowed chords|Borrowed chord}}
In [[jazz education]], a '''contrafact''' is a [[musical composition]] consisting of a new [[melody]] overlaid on a familiar [[harmony|harmonic structure]].<ref name = "GROVE">{{Citation | contribution = Contrafact | editor=[[Barry Kernfeld|Kernfeld, Barry]] | year = 2002 | title = The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz; | edition = 2nd | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford | id = | volume = 1}}.</ref> Contrafact can also be explained as the use of '''borrowed chord progressions'''.<ref name="Existing Music 1994 pp. 851-870">"The Uses of Existing Music: Musical Borrowing as a Field". J. Peter Burkholder. Notes, Second Series, Vol. 50, No. 3 (Mar., 1994), pp. 851-870. Published by: Music Library Association.</ref>
As a compositional device, it was of particular importance in the 1940s development of [[bebop|bop]], since it allowed [[jazz]] musicians to create new pieces for performance and recording on which they could immediately [[improvisation|improvise]], without having to seek permission or pay publisher fees for [[copyright]]ed materials (while melodies can be copyrighted, the underlying harmonic structure cannot be).
Contrafacts are not to be confused with [[musical quotation]]s, which comprise borrowing rhythms or melodic figures from an existing composition.
In classical music, contrafacts have been used as early as the [[parody mass]] and [[In Nomine]] of the 16th century. More recently, ''[[Cheap Imitation]]'' (1969) by [[John Cage]] was produced by systematically changing notes from the melody line of ''[[Socrate]]'' by [[Erik Satie]] using chance procedures.
In spite of its usefulness, the term "contrafact" has not won wide acceptance in Western classical theory.
== Examples == Well-known examples of contrafacts include the [[Charlie Parker]]/[[Miles Davis]] bop tune "[[Donna Lee]]," which uses the chord changes of the standard "[[Back Home Again in Indiana]]"<ref>{{cite book| last = Rosenthal| first = David, H.| title = Hard Bop: Jazz and Black Music 1955-1965| publisher = Oxford University Press| location = New York| isbn = 0-19-505869-0}}</ref> or [[Thelonious Monk]]'s [[jazz standard]]<ref>Yanow, Scott (2008). [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p106839/biography|pure_url=yes}} "Thelonious Monk" biography], ''AllMusic''.</ref> "Evidence", which borrows the chord progression from Jesse Greer and Raymond Klages's song "[[Just You, Just Me]]" (1929).<ref>{{cite journal|last=Williams|first=Martin|title=What Kind of Composer Was Thelonious Monk?|journal=[[The Musical Quarterly]]|date=1 January 1992|volume=76|issue=3|pages=433–441|doi=10.1093/mq/76.3.433|url=http://mq.oxfordjournals.org/content/76/3/433.full.pdf+html}}</ref> The Gershwin tune "[[I Got Rhythm]]" has proved especially amenable to contrafactual recomposition: the popularity of its "[[rhythm changes]]" is second only to that of the [[12-bar blues]] as a basic harmonic structure used by jazz composers.
==See also== *[[Contrafactum]] *[[Stomp progression]] *[[List of jazz contrafacts]]
